      <bioghist id="aspace_583b1712562fb0eb90d5e853f4f232ee">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>William Addison Dwiggins was born in Martinsville, OH, in 1880. He studied in Chicago at the Frank Holme School of Illustration, where he was influenced, among others, by typographer Frederic W. Goudy. Dwiggins ran his own printing firm in Ohio for a short time, but in 1904 he moved to Hingham, MA – a community near Boston that had embraced William Morris's Arts and Crafts movement. Goudy himself was a resident at the time, and Dwiggins remained in Hingham until his death in 1956.</p>
         <p>Dwiggins worked as a book designer, typographer, illustrator, and writer. He designed and illustrated books for publishers such as Alfred A. Knopf, Random House, and the Limited Editions Club. He also designed a number of typefaces for the Mergenthaler Linotype Company.</p>
         <p>Source: Roy R. Behrens, "Dwiggins, William Addison," in Grove Art Online. Oxford Art Online. Accessed 23 Nov. 2010, <ref actuate="onrequest"
                 href="http://www.oxfordartonline.com/subscriber/article/grove/art/T098010"
                 linkrole="text/html"
                 show="new">http://www.oxfordartonline.com/subscriber/article/grove/art/T098010</ref>.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_2473d9ed2537da2dfe85443e2b81f72f">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The W. A. Dwiggins Collection contains examples of graphic design by William Addison Dwiggins, who worked from the early to mid-20th century. The materials range from original drawings to both business and personal designs.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_48fa4353ac2f319c946e9b36af6ede02">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Organized into two series: I. Design Examples. II. Articles about Dwiggins and Other Design Examples.</p>  
      </arrangement>
